  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the government has laws against money laundering. Virtually every developed country and many developing countries have laws against money laundering.\n\nIn the United States, the primary laws are:\n\n*   **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970:** This is the cornerstone of U.S. anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. It requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports that are useful in identifying and tracking suspicious activity.\n\n*   **The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This law criminalized money laundering for the first time, making it a federal crime to engage in financial transactions with proceeds derived from specified unlawful activities (SUAs).\n\n*   **The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** Passed in response to the 9/11 attacks, this law strengthened the BSA and other AML laws, expanding their scope and increasing penalties for violations. It also added new tools for investigating and prosecuting money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nThese laws are enforced by agencies like the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN), the Department of Justice (DOJ), and the IRS Criminal Investigation division.\n\nThe specific details and scope of anti-money laundering laws vary from country to country, but the general principles are the same: to prevent criminals from disguising the proceeds of illegal activities so that the money appears to come from legitimate sources.",
